        "section_value": "Chief Complaint\nRight ankle pain and swelling following a fall.\nHistory of Present Illness\nThe patient reports that he slipped and fell on an icy patch yesterday, resulting in right ankle pain and swelling. He initially could not walk and required assistance from a friend. Since then, he has been elevating his leg, icing it, and taking ibuprofen. Today, he reports some improvement in his ability to put weight on the ankle, but he is still limping. He denies any numbness in his foot. He has a history of multiple sports injuries, including a previous soccer injury, but cannot recall if he ever injured this ankle specifically. He plays in a community soccer league and his children are starting soccer lessons. The patient reports taking ibuprofen for the pain.\nFindings\nPhysical examination reveals ecchymosis and swelling over the lateral malleolus. Palpation of the ankle is tender. Dorsalis pedis pulse is strong. Capillary refill is less than 3 seconds. Neurological exam is intact. Right ankle x-ray shows no fracture.\nAssessment\nThe patient's symptoms and physical exam findings are consistent with a right ankle sprain.\nPlan",
